default2 Role of AD in heat generationdefault2.1 Biogas can be combusted in a CHP engine to generate heat and power or it can be upgraded to a renewable natural gas equivalent (biomethane) and injected directly into 
defaultthe gas grid. 
defaultThe first commercial-scale biomethane to grid project in the UK started injecting renewable gas in late 2012. 
default2.2 
defaultAD 
defaulttechnology 
defaulthas helped businesses in a range of sectors 
defaultreduc
defaulte
default their energy bills, as well as enhancing their sustainability 
defaultcredentials. Farmers, food and drink processers and water companies are particular leaders in the field, 
defaultas they can recycle organic wastes to generate the power and heat their businesses need
default.
default 
defaultAs well as using the biogas to meet their on-site energy 
defaultneeds, operators can also supply heat to nearby buildings or businesses.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default3 Barriers to heat usedefaultIssues with the Renewable Heat Incentivedefault3.1 There are few technological barriers to the greater use of renewable heat from the AD process – the viability of
default the technology has already been proven in the UK and across Europe. What is holding back the industry is the uncertainties around certain aspects of support under the Renewable Heat Incentive (RHI) and the resultant problems this creates in terms of the a
defaultbility to finance infrastructure developments.
default3.2 At present the RHI only supports biogas projects with a thermal capacity up to 200kW thermal capacity. This means that the vast majority of biogas CHP projects are effectively forced to waste any heat they
default generate, as the cost of developing the heat infrastructure is prohibitive without RHI support. DECC have committed to addressing this issue and allowing support for biogas combustion levels at all levels, but delays to this 
defaulthave not helped
default investment in 
defaultbiogas CHP projects. We have submitted evidence to DECC on this point which we would be happy to share with the Committee if it would be helpful. 
default3.3 Similarly, a lack of a preliminary accreditation mechanism under the RHI is also 
defaultholding back
default the develop
defaultment of the biogas heat and biomethane injection market. DECC introduced a degression system from June 2013, which will see tariffs automatically reduced if budget spend under the scheme reaches pre-determined levels. 
defaultUnlike the electricity Feed in Tariff
default,
default they have not introduced a preliminary accreditation model which would allow developers to 
default‘
defaultlock in
default’
default a tariff rate once they have reached a certain stage in their project. 
defaultThis provides a significant financial risk to project developers, especially for la
defaultrger plants which typically take at least a year to build. 
defaultAccess to food wastedefault3.4 
defaultT
defaulthe development of the whole AD sector is dependent on being able to access food waste from businesses and local authorities
default. O
defaultf 
defaultthe total 
defaultpotential
default energy the industry could generate, over 60% comes from these sources
default. While the first priority when dealing with food waste should of course be to reduce the quantity generated, 
defaultfor example by 
defaultredistributing uneaten food whenever possible, there will alw
defaultays be a large portion of unavoidable food waste (
defaulte.g.
default vegetable peelings, teabags) that must be dealt with. 
default3.5 Government confirmed in their 2011 
defaultWaste Review
default  that AD offer
defaults
default the “greatest environmental benefit” of any food waste treatment
default 
default– 
defaultbut 
defaultat present only 7% of food waste in the UK is treated through AD, while 35% is still landfilled.
default3.6 One of the key ways in which
default government can do this is through the introduction of separate food waste collections, which allow AD operators improved access to a less contaminated feedstock, while also improving the recycling rate for other dry recyclates.
default3.7 A ban on sending biodeg
defaultradable waste to landfill would also deliver similar benefits for the AD industry, as well as wider environmental and economic benefits. A recent 
defaultGreen Alliance report
default  
defaultdemonstrated that UK 
defaultorganisations could save £508m in avoided landfil
defaultl costs and £693m could be generated in the value recovered from sending our food waste to anaerobic digestion. 
default&#xa0;
default3.8 Scotland and Wales are far ahead of England in terms of supporting moves towards these more sustainable waste management practices. Under 
defaulttheir 
defaultZero Waste Plan
default, the
default Scottish Government has provided the 
defaultlegislative framework to support rolling out food waste collections across all local authorities and businesses by 2015 and for banning 
defaultorganic waste to landfill by 2020.
default3.9 Wales has also made important progress in delivering more effective waste managem
defaultent through statutory waste recovery targets. Welsh local authorities are currently required to recover (this includes AD) 52% of municipal waste, rising to 70% by 2024, and 
defaultwhere councils recycle source-segregated food waste using AD, it will fund up to 2
default5% of the council’s food waste treatment costs under 15 year guaranteed contracts. This has helped to facilitate a situation today whereby 88% of Welsh households have separate food waste collections, in comparison to just 13% of households in England. 
